# 2. Technology Stack Decisions

Every technology choice was made after comparing alternatives and validating against what existing booking platforms use in production.

| **Decision 01: Backend Language: Go 1.22+ with Fiber v2** **Decision:  **Go 1.22+ with Fiber v2 framework. **Why:  **Performance, K8s-native ecosystem, low memory footprint, strong concurrency model, compiled binary deployment. Docker, Kubernetes, Terraform, Prometheus, ArgoCD — the entire infrastructure stack is written in Go. The language has first-class support for the tools we use. **Validated by:  ***Vagaro and enterprise booking platforms use Go for high-throughput services. Go is consistently top 3 in salary rankings for backend developers. The Go ecosystem in 2026 is mature for all required libraries.* **B-Edge implementation:  **github.com/gofiber/fiber/v2 for HTTP. golang-jwt/jwt v5 for auth. pgx/v5 for DB. go-playground/validator v10 for input validation. |
| --- |

| **Decision 02: Database: PostgreSQL 15** **Decision:  **PostgreSQL 15 as the primary and only database. **Why:  **Full ACID transactions across multiple tables — critical for booking + deposit + audit in one transaction. Native support for TSTZRANGE, GIST exclusion constraints, JSONB, and row-level security. Used by Fresha, Vagaro, and every major booking platform. CouchDB was evaluated and rejected. **Validated by:  ***Fresha, Vagaro, Zenoti, GlossGenius all use PostgreSQL. StackShare developer surveys. Hacker News: developers who used CouchDB said they would use PostgreSQL if starting again.* **B-Edge implementation:  **PostgreSQL 15 in Docker locally. AWS RDS PostgreSQL 15 in production. golang-migrate for schema migrations. pgx/v5 connection pool. |
| --- |

| **Decision 03: Why NOT CouchDB** **Decision:  **CouchDB was evaluated and rejected. **Why:  **CouchDB has no multi-document ACID transactions. A booking creation in B-Edge touches 4 tables atomically. CouchDB cannot guarantee this. No foreign key constraints means no referential integrity. No SQL joins means complex booking queries require MapReduce views. Eventual consistency is unacceptable for financial data. **Validated by:  ***Apache CouchDB documentation confirms no cross-document ACID transactions. Hacker News developers who used CouchDB in production confirmed they would switch to PostgreSQL. DB-Engines ranking: CouchDB last release December 2023, declining activity.* **B-Edge implementation:  **Decision: PostgreSQL only. No document databases in the B-Edge stack. |
| --- |

| **Decision 04: Migrations: golang-migrate** **Decision:  **golang-migrate/migrate v4 for all database schema changes. **Why:  **All DB schema changes through migration files — never manual SQL in production. Migration files are versioned, reviewed, tested, and deployed automatically. The migration history is tracked in the database. No migration can run twice. **Validated by:  ***Industry standard for Go + PostgreSQL. Used by the Go community as the de-facto migration tool. GoCardless, a major fintech, uses migration-based schema management for zero-downtime deployments.* **B-Edge implementation:  **db/migrations/ folder. Files named 001_initial_schema.sql, 002_add_user_status.sql, etc. make migrate and make migrate-test commands in Makefile. |
| --- |

| **Decision 05: Logging: Zap + Fiber logger** **Decision:  **go.uber.org/zap for application logs. Fiber built-in logger for HTTP access logs. **Why:  **Zap is the fastest structured logger in the Go ecosystem. JSON format in production for log aggregation. Human-readable format in development. Structured logs make debugging and monitoring vastly easier than plain text logs. **Validated by:  ***go.uber.org/zap benchmarks show it as consistently the fastest Go logger. Used by Uber, Netflix, and major Go services in production.* **B-Edge implementation:  **Zap logger initialized in internal/config/. JSON mode when APP_ENV=production. Development mode in development. Logs written to logs/app.log in production. |
| --- |

| **Decision 06: Tracing: OpenTelemetry + Jaeger** **Decision:  **OpenTelemetry SDK with Jaeger as the trace backend. **Why:  **Industry standard for distributed tracing. Auto-instruments Fiber routes and pgx database queries. Shows exactly how long each part of a request takes. Essential for debugging slow queries and identifying bottlenecks before they become customer complaints. **Validated by:  ***OpenTelemetry is the CNCF standard, backed by Google, Microsoft, and Amazon. Jaeger is the most widely used open-source trace backend in Kubernetes environments.* **B-Edge implementation:  **go.opentelemetry.io/otel. OTLP HTTP exporter. Jaeger container in docker-compose. Jaeger UI at localhost:16686 in development. |
| --- |

# 3. Database Design Decisions

These decisions define how the B-Edge database is structured. Each was researched against industry practice and validated before the first migration file was written.

| **Decision 07: Primary Keys: UUID v4** **Decision:  **UUID v4 (gen_random_uuid()) as primary key on all tables. **Why:  **PostgreSQL uses heap storage, not clustered indexes, so UUID v4 does not hurt insertion performance unlike MySQL. UUIDs are safe to expose in APIs — they are not guessable or sequential. They can be generated client-side before database insertion. They are globally unique across distributed systems. **Validated by:  ***PostgreSQL documentation and Bytebase engineering blog confirm UUID v4 has no insertion performance penalty in PostgreSQL heap storage. UUID v7 (timestamp-ordered) will be available natively in PostgreSQL 18 — upgrade path is clear and requires no schema changes.* **B-Edge implementation:  **gen_random_uuid() used in all CREATE TABLE statements. When upgrading to PostgreSQL 18, switch to gen_uuid_v7() with no schema changes required. |
| --- |

| **Decision 08: Timestamps: TIMESTAMPTZ everywhere** **Decision:  **All timestamp columns use TIMESTAMPTZ (timestamp with time zone), never TIMESTAMP. **Why:  **TIMESTAMPTZ stores an absolute UTC instant. TIMESTAMP stores a local time with no timezone context. When B-Edge expands to UAE or KSA, TIMESTAMP columns will show wrong times. TIMESTAMPTZ is always correct regardless of the server timezone or the user locale. **Validated by:  ***Elysiate PostgreSQL SaaS best practices guide. Multiple production incidents documented where timezone-naive timestamps caused booking systems to show wrong appointment times when expanding to new regions.* **B-Edge implementation:  **All created_at, updated_at, deleted_at, expires_at, deposit_paid_at, approved_at columns are TIMESTAMPTZ. Application converts to user local time only in the display layer. Go time.Time maps to TIMESTAMPTZ automatically via pgx. |
| --- |

| **Decision 09: Monetary Values: NUMERIC(10,2)** **Decision:  **All monetary values stored as NUMERIC(10,2). Never float64. **Why:  **Floating point arithmetic is broken for money. 0.1 + 0.2 = 0.30000000000000004 in most languages. A European bank miscalculated interest payments for 3 years due to float rounding, resulting in millions of euros in errors. For B-Edge: deposit amounts, service prices, expense reimbursements — all must be exact. **Validated by:  ***PostgreSQL best practices documentation. Real production incident: European bank rounding error from float money storage accumulated over 3 years. Instaclustr PostgreSQL best practices 2025.* **B-Edge implementation:  **All price, deposit_amount, fee_amount, total_amount, unit_price, subtotal columns are NUMERIC(10,2). Go service layer uses float64 only for display formatting. All calculations done in PostgreSQL or with integer cents. |
| --- |

| **Decision 10: Multi-Tenancy: Shared table with salon_id** **Decision:  **Shared tables with salon_id column on every tenant-specific table. **Why:  **Three multi-tenancy patterns exist: database-per-tenant, schema-per-tenant, shared-table. Shared table is the correct choice for B-Edge launch scale. Database-per-tenant costs too much and requires complex management. Schema-per-tenant adds operational complexity with no benefit at our scale. Shared table with salon_id is industry standard for SaaS at launch. **Validated by:  ***Crunchy Data PostgreSQL multi-tenancy guide. PlanetScale approaches to tenancy in PostgreSQL. daily.dev multi-tenant design patterns 2026. Elysiate SaaS PostgreSQL best practices.* **B-Edge implementation:  **salon_id column on all tables: services, bookings, stores, products, discounts, notifications. Every Go repository query includes WHERE salon_id = $1. salon_id injected into context from JWT token. Never trusted from request body. |
| --- |

| **Decision 11: Double Booking Prevention: GIST Exclusion Constraint** **Decision:  **PostgreSQL GIST exclusion constraint on bookings table to prevent overlapping appointments at the database level. **Why:  **Application-level checks for double booking are vulnerable to race conditions. Two concurrent requests can both pass the availability check before either commits. Database-level constraints are atomic and cannot be bypassed by concurrent transactions. **Validated by:  ***PostgreSQL exclusion constraint documentation. Dedicated research: **"**How to Solve the Double Booking Problem with PostgreSQL**"** (jsupskills.dev, 2025). **"**PostgreSQL GiST Exclusion Constraint: The Database-Level Answer to Double Bookings**"** (amitavroy.com, 2026). High Performance PostgreSQL for Rails by Andrew Atkinson.* **B-Edge implementation:  **Migration adds: CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS btree_gist; EXCLUDE USING GIST (artist_id WITH =, tstzrange(start_time, end_time) WITH &&) WHERE (status NOT IN (cancelled, expired, held)). |
| --- |

| **Decision 12: Slot Holding During Checkout: held status** **Decision:  **Bookings have a held status. Slot is held for 10 minutes during customer checkout. **Why:  **Without slot holding, two customers can simultaneously fill in the booking form for the same slot. Both see it as available. Both submit. One gets an error after spending 3 minutes filling the form. Airbnb solved this problem in 2012. Most small booking platforms still have this bug in 2025. **Validated by:  ***Airbnb engineering: slot holding during checkout. General booking system best practices. The slot state machine concept: AVAILABLE → HELD → BOOKED or RELEASED.* **B-Edge implementation:  **Booking status includes: held. held_until TIMESTAMPTZ column on bookings. Background job releases expired holds every minute. GIST exclusion constraint treats held same as confirmed for overlap prevention. |
| --- |

| **Decision 13: Soft Delete: deleted_at on all core tables** **Decision:  **Soft delete on all core tables using deleted_at TIMESTAMPTZ column. No hard deletes in production. **Why:  **Hard deleting a booking, customer, or service permanently destroys business history. A customer who deletes their account still has past bookings that Rania needs for accounting. A service that is retired still has historical bookings referencing it. Soft delete preserves everything. **Validated by:  ***PostgreSQL schema design best practices. Multiple sources confirm soft delete as the industry standard for SaaS booking systems. Referenced in PostgreSQL community discussions on schema design.* **B-Edge implementation:  **deleted_at TIMESTAMPTZ on: users, bookings, services, salons, stores. All queries include WHERE deleted_at IS NULL. Separate delete endpoints set deleted_at = NOW(). Data retention policy to be defined per table. |
| --- |

| **Decision 14: Pagination: Keyset only, no OFFSET** **Decision:  **Keyset (cursor-based) pagination for all list endpoints. OFFSET pagination is banned. **Why:  **OFFSET pagination requires PostgreSQL to scan and discard all rows before the offset. For a salon with 10,000 bookings, OFFSET 9980 scans 10,000 rows and discards 9,980. This is unacceptable at scale. Keyset pagination uses a WHERE clause on the last seen ID or timestamp, making every page equally fast. **Validated by:  ***Elysiate PostgreSQL SaaS best practices: offset pagination is one of the most common medium-scale SaaS performance mistakes. PostgreSQL performance guides consistently recommend keyset pagination for large datasets.* **B-Edge implementation:  **All booking, notification, product, and audit list endpoints use keyset pagination. Query pattern: WHERE created_at < $cursor ORDER BY created_at DESC LIMIT $size. Cursor is the created_at of the last item on the previous page. |
| --- |

# 4. Bugs Pre-Solved Before Building

These are real bugs that have occurred in production booking and financial systems. Each is documented with a real case, the fix, and the B-Edge rule that prevents it. None of these will appear in B-Edge because they are designed out before the first line of code.

*⚡ A bug found during design costs $100 to fix. The same bug in production costs $10,000. All 11 bugs below were pre-solved at design cost.*

| **Bug 01: Float Money Rounding — Silent Accumulation** **What happens:  **Floating point arithmetic produces rounding errors. Each error is tiny. Over thousands of transactions they accumulate into significant discrepancies. **Real case:  ***A major European bank discovered they had been miscalculating interest payments for over 3 years due to float rounding. The error passed all unit tests and regulatory audits. Total cost: millions of euros.* **Fix:  **Store all monetary values as NUMERIC(10,2) in PostgreSQL. Never use float64 for money calculations in Go. **B-Edge rule:  **All price, deposit, fee, total columns are NUMERIC(10,2). Go service layer never performs arithmetic on float64 money values. Calculations delegated to PostgreSQL. |
| --- |

| **Bug 02: Double Booking Under Concurrency** **What happens:  **Two customers book the same slot simultaneously. Both pass the availability check before either commits. Both bookings are confirmed. Artist arrives to find two customers waiting. **Real case:  ***Ticketmaster, Airbnb, Delta Airlines have all had concurrency-related double booking incidents. For a bridal makeup artist, this is catastrophic.* **Fix:  **PostgreSQL GIST exclusion constraint on bookings table. SELECT FOR UPDATE in booking transaction. Constraint enforced at database level — no application-layer race condition possible. **B-Edge rule:  **EXCLUDE USING GIST constraint in bookings migration. Booking creation transaction uses SELECT FOR UPDATE. Unique partial index as additional guard. |
| --- |

| **Bug 03: Slot Stolen During Checkout** **What happens:  **Customer A spends 3 minutes filling the booking form. Customer B books the same slot during those 3 minutes. Customer A submits and gets an error. Frustration. Lost booking. **Real case:  ***A common UX failure in small booking platforms. Most platforms built before 2015 have this bug. Airbnb solved it with temporary holds in 2012.* **Fix:  **Introduce held booking status. Slot is held for 10 minutes when customer begins checkout. Background job releases expired holds. **B-Edge rule:  **Booking status includes held with held_until timestamp. GIST constraint treats held same as confirmed. Customer has 10 minutes to complete checkout before hold expires. |
| --- |

| **Bug 04: Wrong Appointment Time After Timezone Expansion** **What happens:  **Booking stored as local time without timezone. System expands to a new country. All historical bookings show wrong times. Customers arrive at wrong time. **Real case:  ***iCal integration issues where last-minute changes in high-demand periods did not sync properly due to timezone-naive timestamps. Common in booking systems that expand internationally.* **Fix:  **Store all timestamps as TIMESTAMPTZ (UTC). Convert to local time only in the display layer. **B-Edge rule:  **All timestamp columns are TIMESTAMPTZ. Go time.Time maps to TIMESTAMPTZ via pgx. Display conversion happens in Angular PWA layer only. |
| --- |

| **Bug 05: Booking Transaction Fails When WhatsApp is Down** **What happens:  **WhatsApp API call is inside the booking database transaction. WhatsApp has a 2 second timeout. Every booking during that window fails. Customers think the platform is broken. **Real case:  ***Common in small booking platforms built by developers who put external API calls inside database transactions. Invisible in testing, catastrophic under real conditions.* **Fix:  **Notifications are queued asynchronously. Transaction commits the booking first. Background worker sends the notification after. **B-Edge rule:  **Booking transaction creates a notification record with status pending. Separate background worker sends WhatsApp and SMS. Transaction never waits for notification delivery. |
| --- |

| **Bug 06: Deposit Disputes Without Audit Trail** **What happens:  **Customer says they paid the deposit. System shows it as unpaid. No audit log exists. Impossible to determine what happened. Customer trust is destroyed. **Real case:  ***Booking.com had payment disputes with hotel operators that lasted months. No audit trail meant no resolution. Hotel operators risked losing their businesses.* **Fix:  **Append-only audit_events table. Every status change, deposit action, and admin action recorded with timestamp, user, and source. **B-Edge rule:  **audit_events table: id, entity_type, entity_id, action, old_value, new_value, performed_by, source, created_at. Append-only. Never updated or deleted. |
| --- |

| **Bug 07: Salon A Sees Salon B Data** **What happens:  **A query somewhere forgets to include WHERE salon_id = $1. Salon A can see Salon B customers, bookings, and pricing. This is a security breach and a GDPR violation. **Real case:  ***The biggest PostgreSQL SaaS mistake: failing to make tenant boundaries explicit in schema design, indexes, queries, and roles.* **Fix:  **salon_id on every table. Every repository query includes salon_id. salon_id injected from JWT context, never trusted from request body. **B-Edge rule:  **Go service layer context always carries salon_id from JWT. Repository methods accept ctx and extract salon_id. Code review enforces this on every PR. |
| --- |

| **Bug 08: N+1 Queries Slow Down Under Load** **What happens:  **Booking list loads 20 bookings. For each booking, a separate query fetches the artist. Another fetches the service. 1 + 20 + 20 = 41 queries instead of 1. Invisible at 10 salons. Database crashes at 200. **Real case:  ***A 2.1 second query cost a SaaS company $18K in one week due to missing index and N+1 pattern. Query was fine in development with small data.* **Fix:  **Every list endpoint uses SQL JOINs in a single query. Never load related entities in a loop. **B-Edge rule:  **B-Edge rule: every repository function that returns a list uses a single JOIN query. PR review rejects any loop-based data fetching. |
| --- |

| **Bug 09: Hard Delete Destroys Business History** **What happens:  **Artist deletes a service. All historical bookings referencing that service lose their service name and price. Accounting is broken. Legal disputes have no record. **Real case:  ***Standard issue in systems without soft delete. Irreversible once it happens.* **Fix:  **Soft delete with deleted_at on all core tables. Hard delete never happens in production. **B-Edge rule:  **deleted_at TIMESTAMPTZ on users, bookings, services, salons, stores. All queries filter WHERE deleted_at IS NULL. Admin delete sets deleted_at = NOW(). |
| --- |

| **Bug 10: Connection Exhaustion Under Load** **What happens:  **Without PgBouncer, each Go instance opens multiple direct PostgreSQL connections. Under high load, connections are exhausted. PostgreSQL refuses new connections. Platform goes down. **Real case:  ***Standard production issue for Go + PostgreSQL without a connection pooler. Common in applications that scale to multiple instances without anticipating connection limits.* **Fix:  **PgBouncer connection pooler in front of PostgreSQL. pgx pool configured with sensible max connections. **B-Edge rule:  **PgBouncer in docker-compose.yml from day one. pgx pool max_conns configured via DB_MAX_CONNECTIONS env var. PgBouncer in K8s deployment manifest. |
| --- |

| **Bug 11: Long Transaction Blocks VACUUM** **What happens:  **A background job holds a transaction open for minutes. PostgreSQL VACUUM cannot clean dead rows while the transaction is open. Table bloat grows silently. Queries slow down over weeks. **Real case:  ***Common in systems where batch jobs run inside long transactions. Invisible for months, then suddenly queries take 10x longer.* **Fix:  **All external API calls happen outside database transactions. Transactions stay open for milliseconds only. **B-Edge rule:  **B-Edge rule: database transactions contain only database operations. WhatsApp, SMS, email, and any I/O happen outside transactions. Background jobs use separate short transactions per item. |
| --- |

# 5. Migration Rules

These rules apply to every migration file written for B-Edge. Breaking any of these rules can bring down production. All are validated against real production incidents at GoCardless, GitLab, Handshake, and Doctolib.

*⚡ GitLab production incident 2025-09-08: A migration failed to acquire a database lock on a busy table. Deployments were blocked until the migration was manually resolved.*

| **Migration Rule 01: Always CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY** **Wrong:  ** CREATE INDEX idx_bookings_artist ON bookings(artist_id); **Correct:  ** CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_bookings_artist ON bookings(artist_id); **Why:  **Standard CREATE INDEX acquires a SHARE lock that blocks all writes for the entire build duration. CONCURRENTLY builds the index without blocking writes. Note: CONCURRENTLY cannot run inside a transaction block — the migration must disable transactions for this statement. |
| --- |

| **Migration Rule 02: Always add SET lock_timeout** **Wrong:  ** ALTER TABLE bookings ADD COLUMN approved_by UUID; **Correct:  ** SET lock_timeout = '5s'; ALTER TABLE bookings ADD COLUMN approved_by UUID; **Why:  **Without a lock timeout, a migration waiting to acquire a lock will queue indefinitely, blocking all queries on that table until it succeeds or the process is killed. A 5 second timeout makes the migration fail fast and cleanly. |
| --- |

| **Migration Rule 03: Add foreign keys with NOT VALID then VALIDATE** **Wrong:  ** ALTER TABLE bookings ADD FOREIGN KEY (artist_id) REFERENCES users(id); **Correct:  ** ALTER TABLE bookings ADD FOREIGN KEY (artist_id) REFERENCES users(id) NOT VALID; ALTER TABLE bookings VALIDATE CONSTRAINT bookings_artist_id_fkey; **Why:  **Adding a foreign key with direct validation acquires an ACCESS EXCLUSIVE lock while scanning the entire table. NOT VALID adds the constraint for new rows only (fast, minimal lock). VALIDATE then checks existing rows with a weaker SHARE UPDATE EXCLUSIVE lock that allows reads and writes to continue. |
| --- |

| **Migration Rule 04: Never add NOT NULL without a default on large tables** **Wrong:  ** ALTER TABLE bookings ALTER COLUMN deposit_method SET NOT NULL; **Correct:  ** ALTER TABLE bookings ADD CONSTRAINT chk_deposit_method CHECK (deposit_method IS NOT NULL) NOT VALID; ALTER TABLE bookings VALIDATE CONSTRAINT chk_deposit_method; ALTER TABLE bookings ALTER COLUMN deposit_method SET NOT NULL; **Why:  **Adding NOT NULL directly requires a full table scan under an exclusive lock. The 4-step pattern (CHECK NOT VALID, VALIDATE, SET NOT NULL, DROP CHECK) avoids the scan because PostgreSQL trusts the validated constraint and makes SET NOT NULL a metadata-only operation. |
| --- |

| **Migration Rule 05: Add UNIQUE constraint via index first** **Wrong:  ** ALTER TABLE users ADD CONSTRAINT uniq_email UNIQUE (email); **Correct:  ** CREATE UNIQUE INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_users_email ON users(email); ALTER TABLE users ADD CONSTRAINT uniq_email UNIQUE USING INDEX idx_users_email; **Why:  **Direct ADD CONSTRAINT UNIQUE builds the index under ACCESS EXCLUSIVE lock. Building the index CONCURRENTLY first and then attaching the constraint is instant because the index already exists. |
| --- |

| **Migration Rule 06: Never drop a column before removing code references** **Wrong:  ** ALTER TABLE bookings DROP COLUMN legacy_field; **Correct:  ** Step 1 (deploy code that ignores the column): -- No migration yet Step 2 (after code is deployed): ALTER TABLE bookings DROP COLUMN legacy_field; **Why:  **Dropping a column while application code still references it causes immediate errors. The correct pattern is a two-phase deployment: first deploy code that no longer references the column, then deploy the migration that drops it. |
| --- |

| **Migration Rule 07: Always index foreign key columns explicitly** **Wrong:  ** -- FK created with no index ALTER TABLE bookings ADD FOREIGN KEY (artist_id) REFERENCES users(id); **Correct:  ** ALTER TABLE bookings ADD FOREIGN KEY (artist_id) REFERENCES users(id) NOT VALID; ALTER TABLE bookings VALIDATE CONSTRAINT bookings_artist_id_fkey; CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_bookings_artist_id ON bookings(artist_id); **Why:  **PostgreSQL does NOT automatically create indexes on foreign key columns. Without an index, any query filtering by artist_id, customer_id, salon_id, or store_id on the bookings table performs a full sequential scan. This is invisible with small data and catastrophic at scale. |
| --- |

# 6. Engineering Principles

These are the non-negotiable rules for every file, function, and feature built in B-Edge. Inspired by the B-Edge CLAUDE.md and validated against industry engineering standards.

## 6.1 Go Code Rules

| **Rule** | **Description** | **Why** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Package comment | Every file has a package comment explaining its purpose | Code is read 10x more than written. Future self needs context. |
| Go doc on exports | Every exported function, struct, constant, and error has a Go doc comment | godoc generates documentation automatically. No comment = no docs. |
| No hardcoded values | All configuration via .env. No magic numbers or strings in code | A fee amount hardcoded in Go requires a code deploy to change. A DB value does not. |
| Named constants | Named constants for all magic numbers and strings | if status == "deposit_paid" is a bug waiting to happen. Use a const. |
| Parameterized SQL | All SQL queries use $1, $2 placeholders. Never string interpolation | SQL injection is the most common database vulnerability. Parameterized queries prevent it entirely. |
| Always check errors | Never ignore error returns with _ | Ignored errors hide bugs silently. Every error must be handled or explicitly propagated. |
| Pointer receivers | All service, handler, and repository methods use pointer receivers | Pointer receivers avoid copying structs on every method call. Consistent with Go convention. |
| context.Context first | context.Context as first parameter on all DB and service functions | Context carries request cancellation, timeout, and salon_id. Required for pgx queries. |
| Tests alongside code | Tests written alongside code, not after | Tests written after the fact are tests written to pass, not to validate. |
| No feature without docs | Every feature requires code + tests + swagger docs. All three. | An endpoint without swagger docs does not exist for the Angular team. |

## 6.2 Database Rules

| **Rule** | **Description** | **Why** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Migration files only | All DB schema changes through migration files. Never manual SQL in production. | Manual SQL in production cannot be reviewed, tested, or rolled back. |
| TIMESTAMPTZ always | All timestamps stored as TIMESTAMPTZ (UTC). Never TIMESTAMP. | Timezone expansion breaks TIMESTAMP. TIMESTAMPTZ is always correct. |
| NUMERIC for money | All monetary values as NUMERIC(10,2). Never float. | Float rounding errors accumulate silently over thousands of transactions. |
| salon_id everywhere | salon_id on every tenant-specific table. Every query includes it. | Missing salon_id in one query = data leak between salons. |
| Soft delete | deleted_at TIMESTAMPTZ. Never hard delete in production. | Hard delete destroys irreplaceable business history. |
| FK indexes explicit | CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY on every foreign key column. | PostgreSQL does not auto-index FK columns. Missing index = full table scan. |
| Keyset pagination | WHERE created_at < $cursor. Never OFFSET. | OFFSET scans all preceding rows. Gets slower as data grows. |

## 6.3 Security Rules

| **Rule** | **Source** | **B-Edge implementation** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Passwords: bcrypt only | OWASP password storage cheat sheet | golang.org/x/crypto/bcrypt. Cost 10 in production, 1 in tests. Never store plain or MD5. |
| JWT secrets: 64+ hex chars | NIST digital identity guidelines | JWT_SECRET and JWT_REFRESH_SECRET must be 64+ random hex chars. Validated on startup. |
| Email enumeration prevention | OWASP authentication cheat sheet | Wrong email returns identical error to wrong password. Timing-safe comparison. |
| Refresh token rotation | OAuth 2.0 security best practices | New refresh token issued on every /refresh call. Old token invalidated immediately. |
| httpOnly cookies | OWASP XSS prevention | Refresh token in httpOnly cookie only. Never accessible from JavaScript. |
| Rate limiting | OWASP API security | 100 requests per 15 minutes per IP on all /api/ routes. Configurable. |
| Input validation | OWASP input validation | go-playground/validator on every endpoint. Validated before any business logic runs. |
| salon_id from JWT only | Multi-tenant security best practice | salon_id always from JWT context. Never trusted from request body. Prevents cross-tenant access. |

# 7. How We Work Together (Spark and Edge)

These are the rules that govern how Spark (the AI engineering partner) and Edge (the founder and sole developer) work together on B-Edge. They exist because good software requires both speed and carefulness, and a solo developer needs an AI partner who respects their pace.

| **Rule** | **Description** |
| --- | --- |
| Never rush Edge | Spark never pressures Edge to move faster. Edge is a solo developer. Every decision deserves time. |
| Always ask to double check | Before moving to the next step, Spark always asks Edge to confirm the current step is correct. |
| Research before recommending | Every technical or business decision is researched online and validated against industry practice before Spark recommends it. Never answered from memory alone. |
| Validate DB decisions online | No database schema, table design, or query pattern is presented without first validating it against PostgreSQL best practices and competitor implementations. |
| Validate business decisions online | No business rule (deposit policy, cancellation window, pricing model) is presented without first checking how Fresha, Vagaro, GlossGenius, and others handle the same problem. |
| Edge sets the pace | Spark follows Edge. Spark never leads the speed. If Edge wants to spend a week on requirements, that is the right pace. |
| Doubt everything first | If Spark is uncertain about any decision, Spark searches the internet before answering. Not after. |
| All numbers are defaults | Every number in the system (travel buffer, deposit, cancellation window, fees) came from Rania as a default. All are configurable by any salon. |

# 8. Decision Summary

Complete reference of all decisions made before writing a single line of B-Edge code.

| **ID** | **Decision** | **Status** | **Source** |
